title: Veterinary Surgeons Registration Ordinance (Amendment of Schedule 2) Order 2012 to be gazetted
content_text:
p>
    The Government will gazette on March 16 the Veterinary Surgeons Registration 
    Ordinance (Amendment of Schedule 2) Order 2012 (the Order) to amend parts of 
    Schedule 2 of the Veterinary Surgeons Registration Ordinance (Cap 529) (VSRO), 
    to tie in with the development of veterinary practices and to better protect 
    animal welfare.  A spokesman for the Food and Health Bureau today (March 14) pointed out that 
    the existing system of regulatory control of veterinary practices needs to

the existing system of regulatory control of veterinary practices needs to 
    be kept up to date with modern developments in view of the rapid advancement 
    of veterinary knowledge, evolving veterinary practices, and the growing 
    public awareness of animal welfare issues. The spokesman said, "In this regard, the Government has reviewed the 
    existing regulatory regime in Hong Kong as well as the relevant legislative 
    provisions, and launched a two-month public consultation on proposals to 
    amend Schedule 2 of the VSRO in September last year. The respondents were

amend Schedule 2 of the VSRO in September last year. The respondents were 
    generally in support of the relevant proposals. Taking into account the 
    views and comments received, we have finalised the Order." The Order amends Schedule 2 of the VSRO with a view to: (1) permitting a person to perform certain veterinary acts under the 
    direction or supervision of a registered veterinary surgeon; (2) limiting the veterinary acts that an owner of an animal may perform to 
    the animal; (3) permitting a licensed livestock farmer or an owner of a fish to perform

certain husbandry procedures for the prevention of injury or disease and 
    better management and care of such animals; and  (4) permitting certain public officers and authorised persons to perform 
    certain veterinary acts to assist the Government in fulfilling its public 
    responsibilities relating to public health, public safety, animal welfare, 
    disease monitoring and control. The Order will be tabled in the Legislative Council on March 21. Subject to 
    smooth passage through the negative vetting procedures of the Legislative 
    Council, the Order will commence on May 14.
